## Service Layer

Define domain operations as traits. This makes services injectable, testable
with mock implementations, and decoupled from the HTTP layer.

```rust
use async_trait::async_trait;

#[async_trait]
pub trait UserService: Send + Sync {
    async fn get_user(&self, id: UserId) -> Result<User, ServiceError>;
    async fn create_user(&self, cmd: CreateUserCommand) -> Result<User, ServiceError>;
    async fn delete_user(&self, id: UserId) -> Result<(), ServiceError>;
}

pub struct UserServiceImpl {
    repo: Arc<dyn UserRepository>,
}

#[async_trait]
impl UserService for UserServiceImpl {
    async fn get_user(&self, id: UserId) -> Result<User, ServiceError> {
        self.repo
            .find_by_id(id)
            .await?
            .ok_or(ServiceError::NotFound)
    }

    async fn create_user(&self, cmd: CreateUserCommand) -> Result<User, ServiceError> {
        validate_create_user_command(&cmd)?;
        let user = User::new(cmd);
        self.repo.save(&user).await?;
        Ok(user)
    }

    async fn delete_user(&self, id: UserId) -> Result<(), ServiceError> {
        self.repo.delete(id).await
    }
}
```

**Rules:**
- Services contain domain logic only — no HTTP, no SQL, no serialisation
- One service per domain aggregate
- Services accept command/query objects, not raw strings or HTTP types

